
  <sn><md>## Grep

The `grep` command in Bash (and other Unix/Linux shells) is one of the most powerful and frequently used tools for searching and filtering text. It allows you to search for specific patterns (regular expressions or simple text) within files or input streams. The name **“grep”** stands for **Global Regular Expression Print**.

---

### What is `grep`?

`grep` scans text line by line and prints the lines that match a given pattern. It is extremely useful for:

* Searching within log files
* Extracting lines containing keywords
* Filtering command outputs
* Performing case-sensitive or case-insensitive searches
* Using complex regular expressions
