<sn><md>### Basic Syntax

```bash
grep [OPTIONS] PATTERN [FILE...]
```

**Parameters:**

* `PATTERN`: The text or regular expression to search for.
* `FILE`: One or multiple files to search within.
  If no file is given, `grep` reads from standard input (stdin).</md></sn><sn><md>### Common Options

| Option      | Description                            |
| ----------- | -------------------------------------- |
| `-i`        | Ignore case distinctions               |
| `-r` / `-R` | Recursively search directories         |
| `-n`        | Show line numbers                      |
| `-v`        | Invert match (show non-matching lines) |
| `-l`        | Print filenames with matches only      |
| `-c`        | Count number of matching lines         |
| `-w`        | Match whole words only                 |
| `-x`        | Match the entire line exactly          |
| `-e`        | Use multiple patterns                  |
| `--color`   | Highlight matched text                 |
</md></sn><sn><md>### Performance Tips

* Use `-F` when searching for fixed strings — faster than regex.
* Combine `grep` with `xargs` for large datasets:

  ```bash
  find . -type f -name "*.txt" | xargs grep "pattern"
  ```
* Use `--binary-files=without-match` to skip binary files.
